SIMPLE: propagation
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Propagation
<hw>Prop`a*ga"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>propagatio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>propagation</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of propagating; continuance or
multiplication of the kind by generation or successive production;
<as>as, the <ex>propagation</ex> of animals or plants</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There is not in nature any spontaneous generation, but all come by
<qex>propagation</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Ray.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The spreading abroad, or extension, of anything;
diffusion; dissemination; <as>as, the <ex>propagation</ex> of sound; the
<ex>propagation</ex> of the gospel.</as></def>
<rj><au>Bacon.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Propagative</ent>⟦br⟧
